    {"name": "Rhabdomyolysis",            "aliases": ["myoglobinuria"],
     "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Rhabdomyolysis"), ("Mx", "treatment of Rhabdomyolysis")],
     "summary": "Breakdown of skeletal muscle → release of myoglobin (nephrotoxic), CK, K⁺, phosphate. Causes: trauma/crush injury, prolonged immobility, seizures, severe exertion (exertional rhabdomyolysis - marathon running, military training), drugs (statins, alcohol, cocaine, amphetamines, ecstasy), heat stroke, hypothermia, metabolic (hypokalaemia, hyponatraemia, hypophosphataemia), toxins (snakebite), infections, NMS/malignant hyperthermia. Sx: myalgia, weakness, 'cola'-coloured urine (myoglobinuria - positive dipstick for blood but no RBCs on microscopy). ↑CK (>5× ULN, often >10,000 IU/L in severe), ↑myoglobin, ↑K⁺, ↑PO₄, ↑urate, ↑creatinine (AKI). Mx: aggressive IV fluid resuscitation (0.9% NaCl or LR - 1-2 L/hr; maintain UO >0.5 mL/kg/hr, target 200-300 mL/hr until myoglobin cleared); correct electrolytes; urine alkalinisation (bicarbonate - controversial); treat AKI; avoid nephrotoxins; dialysis if refractory AKI."},

