    {"name": "Bowel adhesions", "aliases": ["intestinal adhesions", "peritoneal adhesions", "abdominal adhesions", "post-surgical adhesions", "adhesive bowel obstruction"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Bowel adhesions"), ("Mx", "treatment of Bowel adhesions")], "summary": "Fibrous bands forming between bowel loops/abdominal structures after peritoneal injury. Causes: most commonly post-surgical (80% - laparotomy, appendicectomy, gynaecological surgery), also peritonitis, endometriosis, IBD, radiation. Sx: can be asymptomatic, acute SBO (abdominal pain, distension, vomiting, obstipation), or chronic recurrent episodes. Ix: clinical + AXR (air-fluid levels) or CT abdomen (CT preferred - shows transition point, loop dilatation). Mx: conservative (IV fluids, NGT decompression) for partial obstruction; surgery (adhesiolysis) for complete/failed conservative. Complications: recurrent SBO, bowel strangulation/ischaemia, female infertility (peritubal adhesions). Note: most common cause of SBO in developed countries (~75%)."},
    {"name": "Hemifacial spasm", "aliases": ["HFS", "facial hemispasm"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Hemifacial spasm"), ("Mx", "treatment of Hemifacial spasm")], "summary": "Involuntary twitching/contraction of muscles on one side of face. Causes: most commonly vascular compression of facial nerve (CN VII) at root entry zone (AICA or PICA most common); rarely facial nerve tumour, MS, Bell's palsy sequelae. Sx: begins with orbicularis oculi twitching → spreads to ipsilateral cheek/mouth/platysma; initially intermittent, becomes continuous; distinctive synchronous co-contraction. Ix: clinical; MRI brain/MRA (vascular loop at CPA); EMG (lateral spread response - pathognomonic). Mx: botulinum toxin injections (1st-line - very effective; 3-4 monthly injections); microvascular decompression (MVD) of facial nerve (definitive surgical cure - 90% success). Note: benign essential blepharospasm is bilateral (different diagnosis); starts in eye then spreads."},
    {"name": "Filariasis", "aliases": ["lymphatic filariasis", "elephantiasis", "bancroftian filariasis", "brugian filariasis", "lymphoedema from filariasis"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Filariasis"), ("Mx", "treatment of Filariasis")], "summary": "Parasitic infection by filarial nematodes transmitted by mosquitoes. Types: lymphatic filariasis (Wuchereria bancrofti - most common; Brugia malayi/timori) → lymphoedema/elephantiasis; loiasis (Loa loa - eye worm; West/Central Africa); onchocerciasis (river blindness - Onchocerca volvulus). Epidemiology: endemic tropics/subtropics; 120 million infected worldwide. Sx: acute → fever, lymphangitis, lymphadenitis; chronic → lymphoedema (progressive; arms, legs, genitalia - elephantiasis; hydrocele); tropical pulmonary eosinophilia. Ix: microfilariae on nocturnal blood smear (10pm–2am); antigen tests (circulating filarial antigen); serology; ultrasound (dancing worm sign - live adult worms in lymphatics). Mx: diethylcarbamazine (DEC; also ivermectin/albendazole). Note: WHO Global Programme to Eliminate Lymphatic Filariasis (mass drug administration - DEC + albendazole or ivermectin + albendazole)."},
    {"name": "Transient tachypnoea of the newborn", "aliases": ["wet lung disease", "TTNB", "neonatal wet lung"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Transient tachypnoea of the newborn"), ("Mx", "treatment of Transient tachypnoea of the newborn")], "summary": "Benign self-limiting respiratory distress from delayed clearance of foetal lung fluid. Pathophysiology: foetal lung fluid normally cleared via labour (catecholamine surge → ↑Na+ channels, also chest compression); delayed clearance → ↓lung compliance → ↑respiratory work. Risk factors: elective Caesarean section (no labour → ↓catecholamine surge), precipitate labour, maternal diabetes/asthma, male sex, prematurity. Sx: tachypnoea (>60/min), mild respiratory distress, oxygen requirement; onset within hours of birth; resolves within 12-72 hours. Ix (CXR): prominent perihilar streaking (vascular congestion), fluid in fissures, hyperinflation. Mx: supportive (supplemental oxygen, monitoring); most resolve within 48-72 hours. Note: Caesarean without labour increases TTN risk 3-4× - discuss elective CS timing (37+ weeks gestation); distinct from RDS (premature surfactant deficiency)."},
    {"name": "Medullary sponge kidney", "aliases": ["MSK", "Cacchi-Ricci disease", "renal tubular ectasia", "sponge kidney"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Medullary sponge kidney"), ("Mx", "treatment of Medullary sponge kidney")], "summary": "Congenital renal tubular malformation with cystic dilatation of collecting tubules in renal medulla. Pathophysiology: cystic/sponge-like dilatation of papillary collecting ducts → urinary stasis → calcium deposition + calculi formation. Sx: usually incidental; recurrent nephrolithiasis (calcium oxalate/phosphate); recurrent UTIs; haematuria; incomplete distal RTA (20%); risk of hypercalciuria + nephrocalcinosis. Ix: CT urogram (classic 'paintbrush' appearance of ectatic tubules filling with contrast in medullary papillae; calcifications). Mx: high fluid intake (2-2.5 L/day); thiazide diuretics (hypercalciuria); citrate supplementation (if low urinary citrate/RTA); treat stones as they occur. Note: associated with hemihypertrophy, Beckwith-Wiedemann syndrome; generally benign prognosis - rarely leads to CKD unless recurrent infection/obstruction."},
    {"name": "Liddle syndrome", "aliases": ["Liddle's syndrome", "pseudohyperaldosteronism type I", "familial hypertension with hypokalaemia", "ENaC gain-of-function"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Liddle syndrome"), ("Mx", "treatment of Liddle syndrome")], "summary": "Rare autosomal dominant channelopathy causing early-onset severe hypertension with hypokalaemia. Pathophysiology: gain-of-function mutation in β or γ subunit of epithelial sodium channel (ENaC) in collecting duct → ENaC constitutively open → ↑Na+ reabsorption → ↑BP, ↓K+, ↓aldosterone (suppressed by ECF expansion). Sx: severe hypertension in young patients; hypokalaemia; metabolic alkalosis; low plasma renin + low aldosterone (cf. primary hyperaldosteronism: low renin but HIGH aldosterone). Ix: genetic testing (SCNN1B/SCNN1G mutations); aldosterone:renin ratio (low aldosterone and low renin). Mx: ENaC blockers (triamterene or amiloride - block ENaC directly; do NOT respond to spironolactone); low sodium diet; NOT spironolactone. Note: distinguishing from primary hyperaldosteronism critical - Liddle's has LOW aldosterone + responds only to ENaC blockers, not spironolactone."},
    {"name": "Buerger disease", "aliases": ["thromboangiitis obliterans", "TAO", "Buerger's disease"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Buerger disease"), ("Mx", "treatment of Buerger disease")], "summary": "Non-atherosclerotic, segmental, inflammatory occlusive disease of small-medium vessels of limbs. Pathophysiology: inflammatory thrombosis of small/medium arteries + veins of distal extremities; strongly linked to tobacco use (all forms including smokeless tobacco). Epidemiology: young men (<45 years); smokers (virtually never occurs in non-smokers); more prevalent in Middle East, Asia. Sx: claudication (calf, foot, arch); rest pain, ischaemic ulceration/gangrene of digits; Raynaud's phenomenon; migratory superficial thrombophlebitis. Ix: clinical + angiography (corkscrew collateral vessels - pathognomonic); exclude atherosclerosis; exclude hypercoagulable states. Mx: SMOKING CESSATION (most critical - disease remits with cessation; progresses with continued smoking); wound care; iloprost IV (for critical ischaemia); amputation if advanced gangrene. Note: tobacco use is sine qua non - complete cessation is only effective treatment; even electronic cigarettes/smokeless tobacco maintain the disease."},
    {"name": "Sturge-Weber syndrome", "aliases": ["SWS", "encephalotrigeminal angiomatosis", "Sturge-Weber-Dimitri syndrome", "facial port-wine stain with brain angioma"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Sturge-Weber syndrome"), ("Mx", "treatment of Sturge-Weber syndrome")], "summary": "Rare congenital neurocutaneous syndrome (phakomatosis) caused by somatic GNAQ mutation. Features (triad): port-wine stain (naevus flammeus) in V1 distribution (forehead ± eyelid), leptomeningeal angiomata (ipsilateral - causing seizures, progressive neurological deficit), glaucoma (ipsilateral - congenital angle anomaly). Pathophysiology: somatic GNAQ c.548G>A mutation → aberrant vascular development. Sx: seizures (90% - contralateral to facial stain; onset typically first year; often refractory), developmental delay/intellectual disability, contralateral hemiplegia, glaucoma. Ix: MRI brain with gadolinium (leptomeningeal enhancement, cortical calcification - 'tram-track' calcification on CT), ophthalmology assessment. Mx: anticonvulsants; aspirin (low-dose - ↓stroke-like episodes); laser treatment for port-wine stain; glaucoma management. Note: port-wine stain in V1 distribution → always ophthalmology review (glaucoma) + consider MRI; not all port-wine stains indicate SWS."},
    {"name": "Fibrous dysplasia", "aliases": ["fibrous dysplasia of bone", "monostotic fibrous dysplasia", "polyostotic fibrous dysplasia", "GNAS fibrous dysplasia"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Fibrous dysplasia"), ("Mx", "treatment of Fibrous dysplasia")], "summary": "Benign skeletal disorder with replacement of normal bone by fibro-osseous tissue. Pathophysiology: somatic GNAS1 mutation → constitutively active Gsα → ↑cAMP → abnormal osteoblast differentiation → fibrous tissue replaces medullary bone → structural weakness. Types: monostotic (one bone - most common; 70-80%); polyostotic (multiple bones; ±McCune-Albright syndrome with café-au-lait spots + endocrinopathy). Sx: bone pain, deformity (leg - 'shepherd's crook' deformity of proximal femur), pathological fractures; incidental XR finding. XR: 'ground-glass' appearance, endosteal scalloping, cortical thinning. Mx: bisphosphonates (pamidronate/zoledronic acid - reduce pain + ↑bone density); surgical stabilisation for weight-bearing bones at fracture risk. Complications: malignant transformation (rare - <1%; usually fibrosarcoma). Note: associated with McCune-Albright syndrome (polyostotic FD + café-au-lait + precocious puberty ± other endocrinopathies)."},
    {"name": "Pseudoxanthoma elasticum", "aliases": ["PXE", "Gronblad-Strandberg syndrome", "ABCC6 deficiency"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Pseudoxanthoma elasticum"), ("Mx", "treatment of Pseudoxanthoma elasticum")], "summary": "Rare autosomal recessive connective tissue disorder affecting elastic fibres. Pathophysiology: ABCC6 mutation → defective cellular export of ATP → ↓pyrophosphate (mineralisation inhibitor) → progressive calcification and fragmentation of elastic fibres in skin, eyes, cardiovascular system. Sx: skin (yellowish papules in flexural areas - 'plucked chicken skin'; neck, axillae, antecubital fossa; skin laxity); eyes (angioid streaks on fundus - breaks in Bruch's membrane; visual loss from CNV); cardiovascular (premature atherosclerosis, claudication, angina, stroke, GI haemorrhage). Ix: skin biopsy (calcified elastic fibres - von Kossa stain); genetic testing (ABCC6). Mx: no disease-modifying treatment; ophthalmology monitoring (anti-VEGF for CNV); cardiovascular risk reduction. Note: angioid streaks are pathognomonic of PXE (also seen in Paget disease, sickle cell, Ehlers-Danlos, haemochromatosis); physical trauma may trigger CNV."},
    {"name": "McCune-Albright syndrome", "aliases": ["polyostotic fibrous dysplasia with endocrinopathy", "GNAS syndrome", "Albright syndrome"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of McCune-Albright syndrome"), ("Mx", "treatment of McCune-Albright syndrome")], "summary": "Sporadic syndrome from somatic GNAS1 mutation causing triad of polyostotic fibrous dysplasia, café-au-lait spots, and peripheral precocious puberty. Pathophysiology: postzygotic somatic GNAS1 mutation → constitutive Gsα activation → ↑cAMP in affected tissues → autonomous hormone hypersecretion. Sx: (1) polyostotic fibrous dysplasia (bone - shepherd's crook deformity, fractures, pain); (2) café-au-lait spots (large, jagged 'coast of Maine' border - cf. NF1's smooth 'coast of California'); (3) GnRH-independent precocious puberty (girls > boys; ovarian cysts → early menses, breast development, advanced bone age). Additional endocrinopathies: hyperthyroidism, GH excess, Cushing syndrome, hyperprolactinaemia, FGF23-mediated hypophosphataemia. Ix: clinical triad; GNAS1 sequencing. Mx: treat each endocrinopathy individually; bisphosphonates for bone disease; aromatase inhibitors for precocious puberty."},
    {"name": "Bowen's disease", "aliases": ["squamous cell carcinoma in situ", "intraepidermal SCC", "erythroplasia of Queyrat", "intraepithelial neoplasia skin"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Bowen's disease"), ("Mx", "treatment of Bowen's disease")], "summary": "Intraepidermal squamous cell carcinoma in situ. Pathophysiology: full-thickness epidermal dysplasia without dermal invasion; risk factors: UV exposure (chronic), HPV (16/18 - especially penile/vulval/periungual), arsenic exposure, immunosuppression. Sx: well-demarcated, erythematous scaly plaque (can be pink or pigmented); chronic, slow-growing; may bleed or develop crusting; any sun-exposed site; erythroplasia of Queyrat = glans penis involvement (bright red, moist plaque). Ix: clinical ± dermoscopy; skin biopsy (full-thickness keratinocyte atypia, mitoses; intact BM on histology - no invasion). Mx: topical 5-fluorouracil (5% cream - 12 weeks), imiquimod (5% cream), photodynamic therapy (PDT - preferred for large/field), curettage + electrodesiccation, cryotherapy, surgical excision. Note: ~3-8% risk of progression to invasive SCC - particularly in immunosuppressed; treat all lesions."},
    {"name": "Granuloma annulare", "aliases": ["annular granuloma", "localised granuloma annulare", "generalised granuloma annulare"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Granuloma annulare"), ("Mx", "treatment of Granuloma annulare")], "summary": "Benign dermatosis characterised by ring-shaped dermal papules with central clearing. Pathophysiology: granulomatous inflammation with palisading histiocytes around central degenerate collagen; aetiology unknown - possibly T-cell mediated delayed hypersensitivity; associations with diabetes (generalised form), thyroid disease, dyslipidaemia, HIV. Sx: asymptomatic annular ring of papules (often misdiagnosed as ringworm - no scale/fungal cause); dorsal hands/feet/ankles (localised); generalised form - widespread (stronger DM association); self-limiting in 50% within 2 years. Ix: clinical; biopsy if uncertain (palisading granulomas - histiocytes + degenerate collagen core). Mx: often none (resolves spontaneously); intralesional/topical corticosteroids; cryotherapy; for generalised: hydroxychloroquine, dapsone, phototherapy. Note: check HbA1c (DM association especially with generalised GA); distinguish from tinea corporis (which has scale and positive KOH)."},
    {"name": "Chilblains", "aliases": ["pernio", "perniosis", "perniones", "COVID toes", "chilblain lupus"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Chilblains"), ("Mx", "treatment of Chilblains")], "summary": "Localised inflammatory skin response to cold, damp conditions. Pathophysiology: repeated cold/damp exposure → abnormal vasomotor response → vasoconstriction followed by reactive vasodilatation → oedema, inflammation. Sx: painful/itchy purple-red lesions on toes/fingers/heels/nose/ears; worse in winter; develop hours after cold exposure; localised swelling, blistering in severe cases. Types: idiopathic (most common); lupus pernio (chilblain lupus - from systemic lupus); COVID-19 associated (COVID toes - acrocyanosis/erythema on toes); familial chilblain lupus (TREX1 mutation). Ix: clinical; consider ANA/ENA if lupus suspected; skin biopsy shows perivascular lymphocytic inflammation. Mx: keep extremities warm; avoid cold/damp; vasodilators (nifedipine 5-20 mg TDS - for recurrent cases); topical corticosteroids for inflammation. Note: distinguish from lupus pernio (chilblain lupus) - associated with SLE, positive ANA - test ANA in persistent or atypical cases."},
    {"name": "Cerebral cavernous malformation", "aliases": ["cavernoma", "cavernous angioma", "cavernous haemangioma", "CCM", "cavernous malformation"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Cerebral cavernous malformation"), ("Mx", "treatment of Cerebral cavernous malformation")], "summary": "Vascular lesion - clusters of enlarged, thin-walled blood-filled sinusoidal spaces without normal intervening brain parenchyma. Pathophysiology: sporadic (80%) or familial (autosomal dominant - CCM1/KRIT1, CCM2, CCM3 gene mutations); prone to repeated small haemorrhages. Sx: incidental (25%); seizures (most common symptom - 50%); focal neurological deficit (depends on location); headache; recurrent haemorrhage. Ix (MRI): 'popcorn' or 'mulberry' appearance with haemosiderin rim (blood breakdown products - mixed signal core; dark rim on T2/GRE - haemosiderin); gradient echo sequences sensitive. Mx: observation if asymptomatic or incidental; anticonvulsants for seizures; neurosurgical resection (accessible lesions + recurrent haemorrhage or drug-refractory seizures). Note: 'popcorn lesion' on MRI (T2) = cavernoma until proven otherwise; avoid anticoagulation if possible; screen family members if familial form (CCM1-3 genes)."},
    {"name": "Hemiballismus", "aliases": ["hemiballism", "ballismus", "hemiballismus-hemichorea", "subthalamic nucleus infarct"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Hemiballismus"), ("Mx", "treatment of Hemiballismus")], "summary": "Involuntary, violent, flinging movements of one limb. Pathophysiology: most commonly subthalamic nucleus (STN) lesion (usually lacunar infarct - STN injury → ↓STN output → ↑GPe activity → ↓GPi inhibition → thalamus disinhibited → involuntary movement); also hyperosmolar hyperglycaemic state (bilateral ballismus). Causes: ischaemic stroke (STN lacunar infarct - most common), hyperglycaemia (HHS/HBG - classically bilateral), haemorrhage, tumour, lupus, drug-induced. Sx: sudden onset violent, flinging, large-amplitude involuntary movements affecting arm > leg; exhausting; consciousness preserved. Mx: treat underlying cause (glucose for hyperglycaemia → often resolves within days); dopamine-depleting agents (tetrabenazine) or dopamine receptor blockers (haloperidol, olanzapine); often self-limiting with stroke. Note: bilateral hemiballismus → think hyperglycaemia (check BGL immediately); MRI STN for unilateral to identify underlying cause."},
    {"name": "Body dysmorphic disorder", "aliases": ["BDD", "dysmorphophobia", "body dysmorphia"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Body dysmorphic disorder"), ("Mx", "treatment of Body dysmorphic disorder")], "summary": "OCD-spectrum disorder characterised by preoccupation with perceived defect(s) in physical appearance. Pathophysiology: excessive focus on perceived flaw (often invisible/minimal to others); OCD-spectrum (similar serotonergic mechanisms); abnormal visual processing (enhanced local processing); high comorbidity with MDD, social anxiety, OCD. Sx: preoccupation (hours daily); repetitive behaviours (mirror checking, skin picking, camouflaging); seeks cosmetic procedures (never satisfied); often housebound; high suicidality. Common areas: skin, hair, nose, genitalia, muscle (muscle dysmorphia - mostly men). Ix: DSM-5 criteria; BDDQ screening tool. Mx: CBT (ERP - exposure + response prevention); SSRIs (high doses - fluoxetine 60-80 mg; fluvoxamine); combined CBT + SSRI for moderate/severe. Note: cosmetic surgery is contraindicated (does not help - symptoms transfer to another body part); suicidality assessment essential."},
    {"name": "Microscopic colitis", "aliases": ["collagenous colitis", "lymphocytic colitis", "microscopic IBD"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Microscopic colitis"), ("Mx", "treatment of Microscopic colitis")], "summary": "Inflammatory bowel disease characterised by chronic, non-bloody, watery diarrhoea with normal endoscopy but abnormal histology. Epidemiology: middle-aged to elderly; female predominance; strongly associated with NSAIDs, PPIs, SSRIs, olmesartan, ranitidine (causal association). Types: collagenous colitis (thickened subepithelial collagen band >10 μm) and lymphocytic colitis (↑intraepithelial lymphocytes >20/100 epithelial cells). Sx: profuse, watery, non-bloody diarrhoea (chronic or recurrent - 4-9 stools/day); nocturnal diarrhoea (distinguishes from IBS); weight loss; normal colonoscopy (diagnosis only on biopsy). Ix: colonoscopy with biopsies (random biopsies throughout colon - right colon preferred; must biopsy even if mucosa looks normal). Mx: stop causative medications (NSAIDs, PPIs, SSRIs - may resolve); budesonide (1st-line - 9 mg/day × 6-8 weeks); bismuth subsalicylate; loperamide. Note: NSAIDs/PPIs most important drugs to stop; budesonide 1st-line but relapse on cessation common - may need maintenance."},
    {"name": "Intestinal lymphangiectasia", "aliases": ["primary intestinal lymphangiectasia", "Waldmann disease", "secondary intestinal lymphangiectasia", "chylous malabsorption"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Intestinal lymphangiectasia"), ("Mx", "treatment of Intestinal lymphangiectasia")], "summary": "Disorder of intestinal lymphatics causing protein-losing enteropathy. Types: primary (congenital - Waldmann disease - dilated submucosal/subserosal lymphatics); secondary (obstructed lymphatics - malignancy, constrictive pericarditis, Whipple disease, retroperitoneal fibrosis). Sx: protein-losing enteropathy → hypoalbuminaemia → peripheral oedema, ascites, pleural effusion; fat malabsorption → steatorrhoea, fat-soluble vitamin deficiencies; lymphopenia (lymphocyte loss into gut) → ↑infection susceptibility; chylous ascites. Ix: ↓albumin + ↓lymphocytes + ↓immunoglobulins; stool α1-antitrypsin (elevated - protein-losing enteropathy marker); endoscopy (white-tipped villi - 'snowflake' appearance); biopsy (dilated lacteals). Mx: low-fat diet + medium-chain triglycerides (MCTs bypass lymphatics - absorbed directly to portal system); treat underlying cause (secondary); octreotide (↓chyle leakage); rapamycin (primary cases). Note: lymphopenia despite normal WBC → think protein-losing enteropathy; MCT diet is cornerstone of management."},
    {"name": "Eosinophilic gastritis", "aliases": ["EoG", "eosinophilic gastroenteritis", "eosinophilic GI disease", "EGE"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Eosinophilic gastritis"), ("Mx", "treatment of Eosinophilic gastritis")], "summary": "GI disorder characterised by eosinophil-rich inflammation of gastric and/or intestinal mucosa. Pathophysiology: Th2-mediated eosinophilic infiltration; often overlaps with eosinophilic oesophagitis (EoE) and food allergy; atopic background common. Types: mucosal (most common - nausea, vomiting, diarrhoea, protein-losing enteropathy), muscular (obstructive symptoms - gastric outlet obstruction), serosal (eosinophilic ascites). Sx: nausea, vomiting, epigastric pain, postprandial fullness, weight loss; peripheral eosinophilia (50%); may have concurrent atopy/food allergy. Ix: upper endoscopy with biopsies (≥30 eosinophils/HPF in gastric biopsy); exclude parasites, IBD, coeliac disease, drugs, lymphoma. Mx: food elimination diet (6-food/elemental diet); corticosteroids (prednisolone 20-40 mg/day → taper); PPIs; montelukast; dupilumab (emerging evidence). Note: often overlaps with EoE - consider concurrent conditions; food allergy evaluation important."},
    {"name": "Myofascial pain syndrome", "aliases": ["MPS", "trigger point pain", "myofascial trigger point syndrome", "muscle trigger points"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Myofascial pain syndrome"), ("Mx", "treatment of Myofascial pain syndrome")], "summary": "Chronic pain condition characterised by trigger points in muscle and associated referred pain. Pathophysiology: 'trigger points' (hyperirritable nodules within taut muscle bands) → localised and referred pain; sensitisation of peripheral + central nervous system; distinct from fibromyalgia (central sensitisation without trigger points). Common sites: trapezius, SCM, levator scapulae, suboccipitals, gluteal muscles. Sx: localised muscle pain with trigger points (palpable nodules - reproduce pain on pressure); referred pain pattern (characteristic for each muscle - e.g., SCM trigger → headache; trapezius → neck/shoulder pain); restricted range of motion. Ix: clinical (trigger point examination - local twitch response, jump sign, referred pain); no specific lab tests. Mx: trigger point injections (dry needling or lidocaine injection); physical therapy (stretching, massage, spray-and-stretch technique); analgesics (NSAIDs, TCAs); address perpetuating factors (posture, ergonomics). Note: distinguish from fibromyalgia (widespread vs localised; presence of trigger points); trigger point injections: evidence moderate but clinically useful."},
    {"name": "Capgras syndrome", "aliases": ["Capgras delusion", "delusion of doubles", "impostor syndrome (psychiatric)", "Capgras misidentification"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Capgras syndrome"), ("Mx", "treatment of Capgras syndrome")], "summary": "Delusional misidentification syndrome - belief that familiar person has been replaced by identical impostor. Pathophysiology: proposed disconnect between face recognition (temporal/occipital - normal visual recognition) and emotional response (limbic system - no familiar emotional response) → brain concludes 'this can't be the real person'. Aetiology: neurodegenerative (DLB, Alzheimer's, PD-dementia - most common underlying cause), psychotic disorders (schizophrenia), TBI, metabolic. Sx: patient correctly identifies person's physical appearance but believes they are an impostor; may become distressed, defensive, aggressive towards 'impostor'. Ix: clinical neuropsychiatric assessment; neuroimaging (underlying cause). Mx: treat underlying condition; antipsychotics; education for carers; reduce confrontation. Note: Capgras = familiar person replaced by impostor; Fregoli = strangers are actually known people in disguise; commonest in DLB - screen for parkinsonism features."},
    {"name": "Cotard syndrome", "aliases": ["Cotard's syndrome", "walking corpse syndrome", "délire de négation", "nihilistic delusion"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Cotard syndrome"), ("Mx", "treatment of Cotard syndrome")], "summary": "Rare neuropsychiatric syndrome characterised by nihilistic delusions - belief that one is dead, does not exist, or has lost organs. Pathophysiology: similar disconnection to Capgras but involving all stimuli → patient feels no emotional response to any sensory input → concludes they must be dead or non-existent. Spectrum: denial of existence of body parts, believing they are dead, denying bodily needs, immortality delusion ('I cannot die because I am already dead'). Aetiology: severe depression (most common), bipolar disorder, schizophrenia, dementia, drugs (aciclovir in renal failure → Cotard-like state). Sx: nihilistic delusions; severe depression; self-neglect (refuses food); malnutrition; occasional self-harm. Mx: treat underlying condition; ECT (electroconvulsive therapy - often effective especially with depression); antidepressants + antipsychotics; olanzapine. Note: ECT often dramatically effective; aciclovir/valaciclovir in renal impairment → neurotoxic → Cotard-like presentation - check renal function, dose-adjust antiviral therapy."},
    {"name": "SAPHO syndrome", "aliases": ["SAPHO", "synovitis-acne-pustulosis-hyperostosis-osteitis", "sterile osteitis with skin disease"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of SAPHO syndrome"), ("Mx", "treatment of SAPHO syndrome")], "summary": "Rare inflammatory disorder combining osteoarticular and skin manifestations. Acronym: Synovitis, Acne, Pustulosis, Hyperostosis, Osteitis. Pathophysiology: possibly autoinflammatory (innate immune dysregulation → inflammatory bone/skin changes); association with Cutibacterium acnes; spectrum with CRMO (chronic recurrent multifocal osteomyelitis) in children. Sx: osteoarticular (anterior chest wall - sternoclavicular joint, manubriosternal joint - swelling/tenderness; spine - osteitis; peripheral arthritis); skin (palmoplantar pustulosis - most common 75%; severe acne, psoriasis). Bone scan: 'bull's head sign' - ↑uptake at manubriosternal + sternoclavicular joints. Ix: clinical; MRI (bone marrow oedema → osteitis); bone scan. Mx: NSAIDs (1st-line); bisphosphonates (pamidronate/zoledronate - bone involvement); DMARDs (methotrexate, sulfasalazine); TNF-α inhibitors (refractory). Note: anterior chest wall pain + palmoplantar pustulosis = SAPHO until proven otherwise; bone scan critical for diagnosis."},
    {"name": "Kikuchi disease", "aliases": ["Kikuchi-Fujimoto disease", "histiocytic necrotising lymphadenitis", "Kikuchi's lymphadenitis", "subacute necrotising lymphadenitis"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Kikuchi disease"), ("Mx", "treatment of Kikuchi disease")], "summary": "Rare, self-limiting, benign lymphadenopathy syndrome predominantly affecting young Asian women. Pathophysiology: aetiology unknown; proposed viral triggers (HHV-6, EBV, parvovirus B19); immune-mediated histiocytic necrotising lymphadenitis; strong association with SLE. Epidemiology: young females (20s-30s); higher prevalence in Asia but worldwide. Sx: tender cervical lymphadenopathy (posterior cervical - characteristic); constitutional symptoms (fever 38-40°C, fatigue, night sweats); rash (less common); no pharyngitis or hepatosplenomegaly. Ix: lymph node biopsy (essential - necrotising histiocytic lymphadenitis without neutrophils; distinguishes from lymphoma, TB, SLE); blood counts (↓WBC - leukopenia common); ANA (20-25% have positive ANA - risk of subsequent SLE). Mx: self-limiting (90% resolve within 1-4 months); analgesics; NSAIDs; short-course corticosteroids for severe/prolonged cases. Note: malignant lymphoma must be excluded (biopsy essential); screen for SLE (ANA, anti-dsDNA) at presentation and follow-up - evolves to SLE in 5%."},
    {"name": "VEXAS syndrome", "aliases": ["VEXAS", "vacuoles-E1 enzyme-X-linked-autoinflammatory-somatic syndrome", "UBA1 mutation syndrome"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of VEXAS syndrome"), ("Mx", "treatment of VEXAS syndrome")], "summary": "Recently discovered (2020) haematoinflammatory syndrome from somatic UBA1 mutation in haematopoietic stem cells. Pathophysiology: somatic (not germline) mutation of UBA1 (X-linked - affects males predominantly; females rarely) → dysfunctional ubiquitylation → innate immune dysregulation → autoinflammation + cytopenia. Sx: adult-onset severe autoinflammatory disease (typically men >50 years); recurrent fever; inflammatory skin lesions (neutrophilic - similar to Sweet syndrome); pulmonary infiltrates; chondritis; DVT/PE; cytopenia (MDS-like; bone marrow shows vacuolisation in myeloid/erythroid precursors). Ix: bone marrow biopsy (vacuoles in precursors - pathognomonic); UBA1 somatic mutation (blood or BM - next-generation sequencing); associated MDS or plasma cell dyscrasia in 25-50%. Mx: no established treatment; corticosteroids (high doses required); JAK inhibitors (ruxolitinib); azacitidine (if associated MDS); allogeneic SCT (curative potential). Note: consider VEXAS in any man >50 with steroid-dependent multisystem autoinflammation + cytopenia; estimated prevalence 1/13,000 males in USA."},
    {"name": "Undifferentiated connective tissue disease", "aliases": ["UCTD", "early connective tissue disease", "undifferentiated autoimmune disease"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Undifferentiated connective tissue disease"), ("Mx", "treatment of Undifferentiated connective tissue disease")], "summary": "Autoimmune syndrome with features of connective tissue disease not meeting criteria for any defined condition. Epidemiology: mostly young/middle-aged women; common in rheumatology practice (20-25% of autoimmune referrals); 25-30% eventually evolve to defined CTD (SLE, SS, SSc, MCTD). Sx: arthralgia/arthritis, Raynaud's phenomenon, fatigue, photosensitivity; positive ANA (typically ANA ≥1:160); may have low-titre specific antibodies (anti-Ro, anti-La, anti-U1-RNP). Ix: positive ANA + clinical features but does not meet classification criteria for SLE/SS/SSc/MCTD/RA/PM-DM; exclude ANA-positive normal variants. Mx: hydroxychloroquine (most patients - treats symptoms, may prevent evolution to definite CTD); NSAIDs (musculoskeletal); sun protection; low-dose prednisolone if needed. Note: ~30% evolve to defined CTD (usually within 5 years); predictors of evolution: anti-dsDNA, anti-Sm, anti-Scl-70, haematological involvement; annual review and repeat ANA/ENA panel."},
    {"name": "Spinal epidural abscess", "aliases": ["SEA", "epidural abscess", "spinal abscess", "epidural spinal infection"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Spinal epidural abscess"), ("Mx", "treatment of Spinal epidural abscess")], "summary": "Purulent infection in the epidural space of the spinal canal - neurosurgical emergency. Epidemiology: increasing incidence (IV drug use, diabetes, immunosuppression, spinal procedures). Causative organisms: Staphylococcus aureus (60-70% - most common; MRSA increasingly); Streptococcus; gram-negatives (IV drug users, diabetics); TB (Pott's disease). Risk factors: IVDU, diabetes, spinal procedures/instrumentation, immunosuppression, adjacent infection (discitis, vertebral osteomyelitis), bacteraemia. Presentation (triad): fever, back/neck pain, neurological deficits (weakness, sensory loss, sphincter dysfunction - late finding → paralysis if untreated); triad rarely all present simultaneously. Ix: MRI spine with gadolinium (investigation of choice - rim-enhancing epidural collection); blood cultures + CRP/ESR. Mx: surgical decompression + drainage (emergency - if neurological deficit or large collection); IV antibiotics (anti-Staph ± broad cover - 6-8 weeks; MRSA: vancomycin); percutaneous aspiration for culture if no deficit. Note: neurological deficit → emergency surgery within hours; antibiotics alone only if no deficit + no surgical candidate; blood cultures before antibiotics."},
    {"name": "Cervical myelopathy", "aliases": ["cervical spondylotic myelopathy", "CSM", "degenerative cervical myelopathy", "spondylotic myelopathy"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Cervical myelopathy"), ("Mx", "treatment of Cervical myelopathy")], "summary": "Progressive spinal cord dysfunction from chronic cervical cord compression. Pathophysiology: degenerative changes (disc herniation, osteophyte formation, ligament hypertrophy - especially OPLL) → progressive cervical cord compression → demyelination, cord atrophy. Sx: insidious onset; gait disturbance (broad-based, unsteady - often 1st symptom); hand dysfunction (loss of dexterity - 'clumsy hands', can't button shirts); sensory disturbance (numbness/tingling - hands); upper motor neurone signs (hyperreflexia, Babinski - lower limb); Lhermitte's sign (electric shock on neck flexion); sphincter dysfunction (late). Ix: MRI cervical spine (spinal cord compression + signal change within cord - T2 hyperintensity = myelomalacia; poor prognostic sign); clinical assessment (mJOA scale). Mx: surgical decompression (anterior cervical discectomy/fusion - ACDF; or posterior laminoplasty) - for moderate/severe myelopathy or progressive; conservative for mild. Note: early decompression prevents irreversible cord damage - refer promptly; cord signal change on MRI (T2 hyperintensity) = poor prognostic factor; natural history is stepwise deterioration."},
    {"name": "Brachial plexopathy", "aliases": ["brachial plexus injury", "Parsonage-Turner syndrome", "neuralgic amyotrophy", "brachial neuritis", "brachial plexus neuropathy", "Erb palsy", "Klumpke palsy"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Brachial plexopathy"), ("Mx", "treatment of Brachial plexopathy")], "summary": "Disorder affecting brachial plexus (C5-T1 nerve network). Types: traumatic (traction injury - birth palsy, motorcycle/contact sport trauma; Erb's palsy - upper trunk C5-6 - 'waiter's tip'; Klumpke's palsy - lower trunk C8-T1 - claw hand); Parsonage-Turner syndrome (neuralgic amyotrophy - idiopathic inflammatory; sudden severe shoulder pain → weakness/atrophy; often post-viral/vaccination); neoplastic (Pancoast tumour, breast/lung metastases - lower trunk → Horner's syndrome); radiation-induced (breast/Hodgkin radiotherapy - delayed months-years). Sx: shoulder pain, arm weakness, sensory loss; Horner's syndrome (T1 disruption - ptosis, miosis, anhidrosis); phrenic nerve palsy (C3-5 - ipsilateral hemidiaphragm paralysis). Ix: clinical + EMG/NCS; MRI brachial plexus (neoplastic/structural); CXR/CT chest (Pancoast). Mx: Parsonage-Turner - analgesia (NSAIDs, opioids, gabapentin), physio; traumatic - urgent surgical repair for root avulsions; neoplastic - treat underlying malignancy. Note: Parsonage-Turner: sudden severe shoulder pain → weakness → partial recovery over months; Pancoast tumour: lower plexus (C8-T1) + Horner's = suspect apex lung cancer."},
    {"name": "Phantom limb pain", "aliases": ["PLP", "phantom pain", "stump pain", "residual limb pain", "phantom limb sensation"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Phantom limb pain"), ("Mx", "treatment of Phantom limb pain")], "summary": "Painful sensation perceived in amputated or deafferented limb. Pathophysiology: central sensitisation (cortical reorganisation - somatosensory cortex maps adjacent limb representations to amputated zone); peripheral mechanisms (neuroma formation at stump, ectopic discharges from severed nerves); maladaptive neuroplasticity. Sx: pain perceived in absent limb (burning, shooting, cramping - variable quality); onset weeks-months post-amputation; distinct from stump pain (residual limb pain from local wound/neuroma - non-referred); phantom sensation (non-painful perception of absent limb - very common 80%). Mx: first-line (mirror therapy - visual feedback treats cortical maladaptive reorganisation; gabapentin/pregabalin; TCAs - amitriptyline); second-line (SNRIs - duloxetine; NMDA antagonists - ketamine infusion, memantine); neuromodulation (spinal cord stimulation, transcranial magnetic stimulation); graded motor imagery. Note: mirror therapy (Ramachandran's mirror box) - effective, non-pharmacological, cheap; pain persisting >6 months despite treatment → specialist pain management."},
    {"name": "Glossopharyngeal neuralgia", "aliases": ["GPN", "vagoglossopharyngeal neuralgia", "CN IX neuralgia"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Glossopharyngeal neuralgia"), ("Mx", "treatment of Glossopharyngeal neuralgia")], "summary": "Rare cranial neuralgia involving CN IX (glossopharyngeal) and occasionally CN X (vagus). Pathophysiology: most commonly vascular compression of CN IX at root entry zone (similar to trigeminal neuralgia); rarely CPA tumour, elongated styloid process (Eagle's syndrome), oropharyngeal tumour. Sx: sudden, severe, electric shock-like pain in throat/tonsillar fossa/tongue base/ear; triggered by swallowing, talking, coughing, yawning; may radiate to ear; cardiac syncope (vagal triggers from CN X overlap - cardioinhibitory form → bradycardia/asystole → syncope; rare but life-threatening). Ix: clinical; MRI brain/posterior fossa (vascular loop, CPA lesion); ECG monitoring during attack (document cardiac effects). Mx: carbamazepine (1st-line - same as trigeminal neuralgia); oxcarbazepine; gabapentin; microvascular decompression of CN IX (surgical - effective if vascular compression); glossopharyngeal block. Note: cardiac syncope complication - pacemaker if severe cardioinhibitory type; rare but severe episodes can cause VF → death; distinguish from trigeminal neuralgia (tongue/throat vs face)."},
    {"name": "Occipital neuralgia", "aliases": ["greater occipital neuralgia", "lesser occipital neuralgia", "occipital headache", "suboccipital neuralgia"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Occipital neuralgia"), ("Mx", "treatment of Occipital neuralgia")], "summary": "Neuropathic pain syndrome from greater/lesser/third occipital nerve dysfunction. Pathophysiology: compression, injury, or inflammation of occipital nerves (C2-C3 roots) → aching, burning, or throbbing pain in occipital/suboccipital region; may be idiopathic or secondary to cervical OA, trauma, muscular entrapment, C1-C2 pathology. Sx: unilateral (more common) or bilateral; constant dull ache with superimposed lancinating/electric shocks; starts in subocciput → radiates to vertex/forehead/retro-orbital; scalp hypersensitivity/allodynia over occiput; tenderness at nerve exit points (occipital notch). Ix: clinical + response to occipital nerve block (diagnostic and therapeutic); MRI if secondary cause suspected. Mx: conservative (NSAIDs, muscle relaxants, local heat); occipital nerve block (local anaesthetic ± corticosteroid - diagnostic + therapeutic); carbamazepine, gabapentin; botulinum toxin injections; rarely pulsed radiofrequency or surgical decompression. Note: tender point at greater occipital notch (halfway between mastoid and C7 spinous process) → diagnostic clue; distinguish from migraine (not lancinating; occipital trigger; scalp allodynia)."},

