    {"name": "Sézary syndrome", "aliases": ["Sezary syndrome", "Sézary disease", "leukemic CTCL"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Sézary syndrome"), ("Mx", "treatment of Sézary syndrome"), ("Staging", "staging of Sézary syndrome"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Sézary syndrome")], "summary": "Aggressive leukaemic variant of cutaneous T-cell lymphoma (CTCL); triad of erythroderma + lymphadenopathy + circulating neoplastic T-cells (Sézary cells). Pathophysiology: CD4+ T-cell malignancy; Sézary cells (cerebriform nuclei) ≥1,000/mm³ in peripheral blood. Sx: generalised erythroderma (intense pruritus - often debilitating), lymphadenopathy, Sézary cells in blood, leonine facies, palmoplantar keratoderma, nail dystrophy, ectropion, alopecia. Ix: skin biopsy (epidermotropism, Pautrier microabscesses); peripheral blood flow cytometry (CD4+/CD7− or CD4+/CD26− clone); T-cell receptor gene rearrangement; PET-CT staging. Mx: systemic (extracorporeal photopheresis - ECP, first-line for erythrodermic CTCL; mogamulizumab, brentuximab vedotin, romidepsin; alemtuzumab for refractory); allogeneic SCT in eligible patients; skin-directed + systemic combined. Note: prognosis poor (median OS 2-4 yr); distinguish from Mycosis fungoides (patch/plaque stage → no leukaemia); erythroderma with pruritus in older adult → exclude Sézary syndrome."},
    {"name": "Primary CNS lymphoma", "aliases": ["PCNSL", "primary central nervous system lymphoma", "CNS lymphoma", "primary brain lymphoma"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Primary CNS lymphoma"), ("Mx", "treatment of Primary CNS lymphoma"), ("Staging", "staging of Primary CNS lymphoma"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Primary CNS lymphoma")], "summary": "Rare extra-nodal B-cell NHL (DLBCL - diffuse large B-cell lymphoma) confined to CNS; no systemic lymphoma. Risk factors: immunosuppression (HIV/AIDS - EBV driven; transplant recipients), but majority are immunocompetent. Sx: focal neurological deficits (most common), cognitive decline, personality change, raised ICP (headache, vomiting), seizures (less common than other brain tumours); in HIV: multifocal ring-enhancing lesions (confused with toxoplasmosis). Ix: MRI brain - homogeneously enhancing periventricular/deep white matter mass (basal ganglia, corpus callosum); CSF cytology (positive in 25% - malignant B-cells), vitreoretinal biopsy; brain biopsy (stereotactic - gold standard; avoid steroids before biopsy - profound response obscures diagnosis 'biopsy-negative lymphoma'). Mx: high-dose methotrexate (HD-MTX)-based chemotherapy (cornerstone - crosses BBB); rituximab; whole-brain radiotherapy (WBR - effective but neurotoxic in elderly); autologous SCT consolidation (younger patients); in HIV: ART + HD-MTX. Note: steroid-induced 'ghost tumour' - dramatic regression on steroids but biopsy becomes non-diagnostic; avoid steroids until biopsy planned; median OS 2-5 yr with treatment."},
    {"name": "Angioimmunoblastic T-cell lymphoma", "aliases": ["AITL", "angioimmunoblastic lymphadenopathy", "AILD"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Angioimmunoblastic T-cell lymphoma"), ("Mx", "treatment of Angioimmunoblastic T-cell lymphoma"), ("Staging", "staging of Angioimmunoblastic T-cell lymphoma"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Angioimmunoblastic T-cell lymphoma")], "summary": "Aggressive peripheral T-cell lymphoma (PTCL); second most common PTCL subtype. Pathophysiology: neoplastic follicular helper T-cells (TFH cells - CD4+CXCL13+PD-1+); arises from germinal centre T-cells; IDH2/DNMT3A/TET2 mutations common. Sx: advanced-stage disease typical; constitutional B symptoms (fever, sweats, weight loss); generalised lymphadenopathy; hepatosplenomegaly; skin rash (macular - immune-mediated); ascites, pleural effusions; polyclonal hypergammaglobulinaemia; autoimmune haemolytic anaemia. Ix: lymph node biopsy (polymorphous infiltrate, arborising high endothelial venules, follicular dendritic cell meshworks, TFH immunophenotype - CD4+CD10+CXCL13+PD-1+); EBV-positive B-cells within tumour; BM biopsy + PET-CT staging. Mx: CHOP or CHOP-like (anthracycline-based); brentuximab vedotin + CHP (for CD30+ PTCL); romidepsin; autologous SCT consolidation in first remission (eligible patients). Note: prognosis poor (5-yr OS ~35%); frequent relapses; EBV-associated B-cell proliferations can develop → EBV-positive DLBCL."},
    {"name": "Extranodal NK/T-cell lymphoma", "aliases": ["ENKTL", "NK/T-cell lymphoma", "nasal NK/T-cell lymphoma", "angiocentric lymphoma", "lethal midline granuloma"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Extranodal NK/T-cell lymphoma"), ("Mx", "treatment of Extranodal NK/T-cell lymphoma"), ("Staging", "staging of Extranodal NK/T-cell lymphoma"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Extranodal NK/T-cell lymphoma")], "summary": "Aggressive EBV-associated lymphoma with NK-cell or cytotoxic T-cell phenotype; predilection for nasal cavity/nasopharynx. Epidemiology: Asia and Latin America > Western populations; EBV universally present (clonal episomal EBV in tumour cells). Nasal type: most common - midfacial destruction ('lethal midline granuloma' - destructive ulceration of nose/palate/sinuses); perforated nasal septum, proptosis (orbital extension). Extranasal type: skin, GI tract, testes - worse prognosis. Haemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis (HLH) complication. Ix: biopsy (angioinvasion/angiodestruction - necrosis, coagulative; NK-cell markers: CD56+, CD3ε+; cytotoxic granules: TIA-1/granzyme B; EBV-EBER ISH+); PET-CT staging. Mx: non-anthracycline-based (P-GEMOX - cisplatin, gemcitabine, oxaliplatin; or AspaMetDex - L-asparaginase, methotrexate, dexamethasone); concurrent RT for nasal-type localised disease; L-asparaginase-containing regimens most effective. Note: resistance to anthracyclines (P-glycoprotein expression); EBV DNA (plasma) monitors disease; prognosis poor for disseminated disease."},
    {"name": "Primary mediastinal B-cell lymphoma", "aliases": ["PMBCL", "primary mediastinal large B-cell lymphoma", "thymic B-cell lymphoma"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Primary mediastinal B-cell lymphoma"), ("Mx", "treatment of Primary mediastinal B-cell lymphoma"), ("Staging", "staging of Primary mediastinal B-cell lymphoma"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Primary mediastinal B-cell lymphoma")], "summary": "Distinct DLBCL subtype arising from thymic B-cells; young adults, female predominance. Pathophysiology: JAK2 amplification (chromosome 9p24.1); PDL1/PDL2 overexpression (immune evasion); related to nodular sclerosis Hodgkin lymphoma (overlapping features - 'grey zone' lymphoma). Sx: anterior mediastinal mass (rapid growth) → SVC syndrome, dyspnoea, chest pain, cough; local invasion (pericardium, lung, pleura, chest wall); rarely extranodal at diagnosis. Ix: biopsy (compartmentalising sclerosis, medium-large B-cells - CD20+CD30+CD15−; PDL1 overexpression); PET-CT staging; differentiate from Hodgkin lymphoma (grey zone challenging). Mx: dose-adjusted EPOCH-R (etoposide, prednisone, vincristine, cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin + rituximab - first-line; avoids RT in complete responders); or R-CHOP then mediastinal RT; pembrolizumab (checkpoint inhibitor - exploits PDL1 overexpression; approved for R/R). Note: consolidation RT debated (significant long-term toxicity: coronary artery disease, second malignancies, breast cancer in young women); PET-CR after induction → RT may be omitted; excellent prognosis in responders (5-yr OS ~80%)."},
    {"name": "Hairy cell leukaemia", "aliases": ["HCL", "hairy cell leukemia"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Hairy cell leukaemia"), ("Mx", "treatment of Hairy cell leukaemia"), ("Staging", "staging of Hairy cell leukaemia"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Hairy cell leukaemia")], "summary": "Rare mature B-cell malignancy; characteristic 'hairy' cytoplasmic projections. Pathophysiology: BRAF V600E mutation (present in >95% - diagnostic). Epidemiology: middle-aged males; rare. Sx: massive splenomegaly (often presenting complaint), pancytopenia (anaemia, thrombocytopenia, neutropenia - recurrent infections); monocytopenia (characteristic); lymphadenopathy uncommon (spleen infiltrated). Complications: recurrent infections (especially atypical mycobacteria - Mycobacterium avium complex, aspergillosis); vasculitis, polyarteritis nodosa. Ix: peripheral blood (hairy cells - villous lymphocytes; TRAP [tartrate-resistant acid phosphatase] stain+); BM biopsy (dry tap - reticulin fibrosis; characteristic infiltrate); flow cytometry (CD19+CD20+CD22+CD11c+CD25+CD103+CD123+ - TRAP+). Mx: cladribine (2-chlorodeoxyadenosine - purine analogue; single course → 85% CR); pentostatin (alternative purine analogue); BRAF inhibitors (vemurafenib - for relapsed/refractory or upfront treatment under investigation); rituximab combinations. Note: excellent prognosis with purine analogues; BRAF V600E = diagnostic; monocytopenia = distinguishing feature of HCL (low monocytes despite infection)."},
    {"name": "Splenic marginal zone lymphoma", "aliases": ["SMZL", "splenic lymphoma with villous lymphocytes", "SLVL"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Splenic marginal zone lymphoma"), ("Mx", "treatment of Splenic marginal zone lymphoma"), ("Staging", "staging of Splenic marginal zone lymphoma"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Splenic marginal zone lymphoma")], "summary": "Indolent B-cell lymphoma arising from marginal zone B-cells of spleen; often presents with massive splenomegaly. Pathophysiology: del(7q) in ~40%; NOTCH2 mutations; association with hepatitis C virus (HCV - screen all patients). Sx: splenomegaly (often massive, symptomatic - abdominal discomfort, early satiety); lymphocytosis with villous lymphocytes in blood; autoimmune cytopenias (AIHA, ITP); minimal peripheral lymphadenopathy. Ix: splenectomy (histology - gold standard; nodular marginal zone pattern); peripheral blood flow cytometry (CD20+IgM+CD5−CD10−CD23−CD103−; villous lymphocytes); BM trephine; exclude HCV (hepatitis C serology). Mx: watch-and-wait (indolent course; asymptomatic); HCV treatment (for HCV+ - antiviral therapy alone can induce lymphoma remission); splenectomy (symptomatic splenomegaly - rapid cytoreduction + diagnostic); rituximab (single agent or R-chemo for HCV-negative or refractory); prognosis good (median OS 10+ yr). Note: HCV association critical - treat HCV first; del(7q) associated with worse prognosis; transformation to DLBCL in ~10%."},
    {"name": "Pigmented villonodular synovitis", "aliases": ["PVNS", "tenosynovial giant cell tumour", "TGCT", "diffuse TGCT", "localised TGCT", "giant cell tumour of tendon sheath"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Pigmented villonodular synovitis"), ("Mx", "treatment of Pigmented villonodular synovitis"), ("Staging", "staging of Pigmented villonodular synovitis"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Pigmented villonodular synovitis")], "summary": "Locally aggressive benign synovial proliferative disorder; now termed tenosynovial giant cell tumour (TGCT). Pathophysiology: CSF1 gene translocation → CSF1 overexpression → monocyte/macrophage recruitment → synovial proliferation; haemosiderin deposition (brown discolouration - 'villonodular'). Types: diffuse TGCT (previously PVNS - entire joint, locally aggressive); localised TGCT (previously giant cell tumour of tendon sheath - discrete nodule, hand/foot). Sites: knee most common (diffuse); hand/wrist (localised). Sx: knee - chronic pain, swelling (haemarthrosis - serosanguinous aspirate), stiffness, locked joint (loose body); insidious onset; age 20-50 yr. Ix: MRI (characteristic - low signal on T1 and T2 from haemosiderin; blooming artefact on GRE/SWI - diagnostic; irregular synovial masses); synovial biopsy (histology - mononuclear cells, multinucleated giant cells, haemosiderin, xanthoma cells). Mx: surgical synovectomy (complete - reduces recurrence; arthroscopic for localised; open/combined for diffuse); pexidartinib (CSF1R inhibitor - FDA approved for diffuse TGCT; significant liver toxicity - REMS programme); radiotherapy (adjuvant - for recurrent/unresectable). Note: recurrence common after incomplete synovectomy (diffuse TGCT); pexidartinib available in Australia via TGA - specialist use only."},
    {"name": "Superficial siderosis", "aliases": ["superficial siderosis of the CNS", "superficial haemosiderosis"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Superficial siderosis"), ("Mx", "treatment of Superficial siderosis"), ("Staging", "staging of Superficial siderosis"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Superficial siderosis")], "summary": "Haemosiderin deposition in CNS leptomeninges and subpial tissues from chronic or recurrent subarachnoid bleeding. Pathophysiology: repeated microhaemorrhages → haemoglobin breakdown → haemosiderin deposits on pial surface → iron-mediated neurotoxicity (free radicals) → progressive neurodegeneration, especially cochlear nerve (VIII), cerebellum, cerebral cortex. Causes: spinal dural defect/tear (most common - CSF-venous fistula, post-surgical/traumatic), intradural tumour (ependymoma, schwannoma), vascular malformation, unknown (idiopathic). Classical triad: sensorineural hearing loss (bilateral, progressive - CN VIII most vulnerable), cerebellar ataxia (progressive), myelopathy (pyramidal signs). Ix (MRI): T2*/SWI - hypointense 'coating' of pial surfaces (brain surface, cranial nerves, cerebellum, spinal cord). Ix: MRI (characteristic T2* signal - 'rim of hemosiderin'); CSF (xanthochromia - chronic; siderophages; elevated ferritin); search for bleeding source (spinal MRI - dural defect). Mx: identify and treat bleeding source (surgical repair of dural defect - stops progression); chelation therapy (deferoxamine - limited evidence); supportive (hearing aids, rehabilitation). Note: progressive and often irreversible once symptomatic; early identification of source critical; now increasingly recognised cause - spinal dural CSF-venous fistula most common treatable cause."},
    {"name": "Seborrhoeic keratosis", "aliases": ["seborrheic keratosis", "seborrhoeic wart", "basal cell papilloma", "verruca senilis", "senile wart"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Seborrhoeic keratosis"), ("Mx", "treatment of Seborrhoeic keratosis"), ("Staging", "staging of Seborrhoeic keratosis"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Seborrhoeic keratosis")], "summary": "Common benign epidermal tumour; clonal keratinocyte proliferation. Pathophysiology: FGFR3 and PIK3CA mutations in sporadic lesions; somatic. Epidemiology: extremely common; increases with age (>50 yr); sun-exposed and non-exposed sites; multiple lesions typical. Sx: well-demarcated, 'stuck-on' appearance; brown-black colour variation; warty/greasy surface; comedone-like openings (horn cysts on dermoscopy); painless; trunk, face, limbs. Sign of Leser-Trélat: sudden eruption of multiple SKs = rare paraneoplastic sign (GI malignancy - stomach, colon). Ix: clinical (dermoscopy - comedo-like openings, milia-like cysts, gyri/sulci pattern, sharply demarcated border); biopsy if melanoma excluded. Mx: reassurance (benign); removal for cosmesis or irritation (cryotherapy, curettage, electrocautery, laser). Note: no malignant potential; dermoscopy differentiates from melanoma (comedo openings - not melanoma); new rapid-onset multiple SKs → consider paraneoplastic workup."},
    {"name": "Dermatofibroma", "aliases": ["benign fibrous histiocytoma", "fibrous histiocytoma", "histiocytoma"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Dermatofibroma"), ("Mx", "treatment of Dermatofibroma"), ("Staging", "staging of Dermatofibroma"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Dermatofibroma")], "summary": "Common benign dermal fibrohistiocytic tumour; spindle cell proliferation in dermis. Aetiology: unknown; possible reactive (insect bite, minor trauma - common history); some considered true neoplasms. Sx: firm, slightly raised or depressed, red-brown papule/nodule (4-10 mm); lower limbs (especially anterior shin) most common; dimple sign (Fitzpatrick sign - pinching = central dimpling as tumour tethered to dermis); mildly itchy; solitary typical; stable or slowly grow. Ix: clinical (dimple sign + dermoscopy - central white scar-like patch, peripheral pigment network); biopsy if atypical (distinguish from DFSP - dermatofibrosarcoma protuberans). Mx: none required; excision if symptomatic, large, or diagnostic uncertainty. Note: dimple/Fitzpatrick sign distinguishes from DFSP (DFSP protrudes on pinching - grows outward - locally aggressive); multiple DFs (>15) associated with SLE, HIV, myasthenia gravis."},
    {"name": "Keloid", "aliases": ["keloid scar", "keloidal scarring", "hypertrophic scar"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Keloid"), ("Mx", "treatment of Keloid"), ("Staging", "staging of Keloid"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Keloid")], "summary": "Abnormal fibroproliferative scar tissue extending beyond original wound margins (keloid) or confined within wound (hypertrophic scar). Pathophysiology: dysregulated wound healing - excessive fibroblast activity, collagen deposition (predominantly type III → remodelled to type I); TGF-β overexpression; keloids: invade surrounding tissue, don't regress; hypertrophic scars: confined, may spontaneously regress. Risk factors: dark skin (Black, Asian, Hispanic - 15-20× risk vs fair skin); sites (sternum, shoulders, earlobes, mandible - 'high-tension' areas); genetics (family history); young adults; prior keloid. Sx: keloid - firm, rubbery, shiny plaque/nodule extending beyond wound; pruritus, pain, tenderness; earlobes (piercings - common), chest, shoulders; hypertrophic - raised red scar confined to wound; resolves over 1-2 yr. Mx: intralesional corticosteroid injection (triamcinolone - first-line; repeat at 4-6 wk); silicone gel sheets (prevention + treatment); pressure therapy; cryotherapy (effective for small keloids); excision (risk of recurrence - combine with adjuvant: steroid injection, RT); laser therapy; 5-fluorouracil (intralesional); low-dose superficial radiotherapy (post-excision - recalcitrant keloids). Note: keloid ≠ hypertrophic scar (grows beyond wound vs stays within); recurrence after excision alone very high (~50-100%) - always combine with adjuvant therapy."},
    {"name": "Telogen effluvium", "aliases": ["diffuse hair loss", "diffuse alopecia"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Telogen effluvium"), ("Mx", "treatment of Telogen effluvium"), ("Staging", "staging of Telogen effluvium"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Telogen effluvium")], "summary": "Diffuse hair shedding from excessive premature shift of hair follicles from anagen (growth) to telogen (resting) phase. Pathophysiology: trigger → synchronised follicle shift to telogen → mass shedding 2-3 months after trigger; normally <15% follicles in telogen - TE: >25%. Acute causes: childbirth (most common - postpartum TE, 2-3 months post-delivery), febrile illness (COVID-19, influenza), major surgery, acute psychological stress, crash dieting, iron deficiency. Chronic causes: hypothyroidism, iron deficiency, malnutrition, medications (retinoids, anticoagulants, lithium, beta-blockers, OCP cessation). Sx: diffuse shedding (positive pull test - >6 hairs per pull), diffuse thinning (non-scarring - follicles intact), hair part widening; 100-300 hairs/day shed (normal <100); scalp not inflamed. Ix: clinical; FBC, iron studies, TFTs, ferritin, zinc (exclude underlying cause); scalp biopsy if uncertain (telogen:anagen ratio >25%); trichoscopy (empty follicles, decreased density). Mx: treat underlying cause; reassurance (self-limiting - regrowth within 6-12 months acute TE); iron supplementation (if deficient); nutritional optimisation. Note: spontaneous recovery within 6 months if trigger removed; distinguish from androgenetic alopecia (patterned, male/female pattern - miniaturisation on biopsy)."},
    {"name": "Androgenetic alopecia", "aliases": ["AGA", "male pattern baldness", "female pattern hair loss", "FPHL", "androgenic alopecia", "pattern baldness", "male pattern alopecia"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Androgenetic alopecia"), ("Mx", "treatment of Androgenetic alopecia"), ("Staging", "staging of Androgenetic alopecia"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Androgenetic alopecia")], "summary": "Commonest form of hair loss; androgen-dependent progressive follicular miniaturisation. Pathophysiology: genetically determined sensitivity to DHT (dihydrotestosterone - converted from testosterone by 5α-reductase in follicles) → follicle miniaturisation → shorter, finer vellus hairs; HLA-related predisposition. Males (Hamilton-Norwood): frontotemporal recession + vertex balding → confluence; Females (Ludwig): diffuse crown thinning (central part widening) - frontal hairline preserved (FPHL). Sx: males - temple recession + crown thinning; females - widening central part, crown thinning, preserved frontal hairline. Ix: clinical (pattern distribution); trichoscopy (follicular miniaturisation - variable hair shaft diameters, perifollicular pigmentation); biopsy if uncertain (miniaturised follicles, telogen:anagen >1). Mx: males - finasteride (5α-reductase inhibitor - 1 mg daily, effective; SE: sexual dysfunction, post-finasteride syndrome - rare but persistent); females - minoxidil topical (2% - first-line for women); both sexes - minoxidil topical/oral; low-level laser therapy; hair transplant (FUE - follicular unit extraction). Note: finasteride contraindicated in pregnancy/women of childbearing potential; dutasteride more potent than finasteride; treatment must be lifelong to maintain benefit."},
    {"name": "Livedoid vasculopathy", "aliases": ["livedoid vasculitis", "atrophie blanche", "segmental hyalinising vasculitis", "PURPLE"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Livedoid vasculopathy"), ("Mx", "treatment of Livedoid vasculopathy"), ("Staging", "staging of Livedoid vasculopathy"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Livedoid vasculopathy")], "summary": "Occlusive vasculopathy of dermal vessels (NOT true vasculitis); painful lower leg ulceration with characteristic atrophie blanche scarring. Pathophysiology: thrombotic occlusion of superficial dermal vessels → ischaemia → ulceration → stellate white scars (atrophie blanche); association with thrombophilias (factor V Leiden, prothrombin mutation, antiphospholipid syndrome, hyperhomocysteinaemia) in ~50% and autoimmune disease (SLE, Sjögren's). Sx: recurrent, painful ulcers (lower legs, especially ankles); livedo reticularis (net-like mottling); atrophie blanche scars (porcelain-white stellate scars with telangiectasia - pathognomonic); summer exacerbation; young-middle-aged women. Ix: clinical + skin biopsy (hyaline thrombi in dermal vessels, fibrin deposition - no leucocytoclastic vasculitis); thrombophilia screen; ANA, APLA. Mx: anticoagulation (low-dose aspirin, low molecular weight heparin, warfarin, rivaroxaban - antiplatelet/anticoagulant); pentoxifylline, dipyridamole; hyperbaric oxygen; avoid venous stasis; vasodilators. Note: not a true vasculitis (no inflammation - occlusive); atrophie blanche = stellate white scar = pathognomonic; screen for thrombophilia in all patients; painful ulcers may be confused with pyoderma gangrenosum (PG - neutrophilic, pathergy positive)."},
    {"name": "Necrobiosis lipoidica", "aliases": ["necrobiosis lipoidica diabeticorum", "NLD"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Necrobiosis lipoidica"), ("Mx", "treatment of Necrobiosis lipoidica"), ("Staging", "staging of Necrobiosis lipoidica"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Necrobiosis lipoidica")], "summary": "Granulomatous dermopathy; strongly associated with diabetes mellitus. Pathophysiology: unknown; microangiopathy and collagen degeneration; possible immune-mediated mechanism; associated with T1DM most commonly (0.3-1%), T2DM less so; can precede diabetes diagnosis. Sx: bilateral pretibial plaques (lower legs - classic site); yellow-brown waxy plaques with telangiectasia; central atrophy + ulceration (prone to recurrent ulceration - traumatic); violaceous border; well-demarcated; slow progression. Ix: clinical; biopsy (full-thickness dermal granulomas - 'tier-like' arrangement, necrobiotic collagen, palisading histiocytes, plasma cells, telangiectasia). Mx: topical/intralesional corticosteroids (triamcinolone - ulcerated → avoid systemic steroids); tacrolimus; fumaric acid esters; anti-TNF (infliximab, adalimumab - severe); PUVA; wound care for ulcers; diabetic control (glycaemic control does not consistently alter NL course). Note: ulceration complicates ~35% (injury prone pretibial location); distinguish from pretibial myxoedema (hypothyroid, non-pitting oedema); association with diabetes - check glucose; glycaemic control doesn't reliably improve NL."},
    {"name": "Hailey-Hailey disease", "aliases": ["familial benign pemphigus", "benign familial pemphigus", "HHD"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Hailey-Hailey disease"), ("Mx", "treatment of Hailey-Hailey disease"), ("Staging", "staging of Hailey-Hailey disease"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Hailey-Hailey disease")], "summary": "Rare autosomal dominant blistering skin disorder from acantholysis. Pathophysiology: ATP2C1 mutation → defective Golgi Ca2+/Mn2+ pump (hSPCA1) → impaired intracellular calcium signalling → desmoglein processing failure → acantholysis (loss of keratinocyte cohesion) in superficial epidermis. Sx: recurrent erosions/crusted plaques in flexures (axillae, groins, inframammary, neck - friction + moisture areas); macerated, malodorous erosions; flares triggered by friction, heat, sweating, UV, infection (Candida, HSV, Staphylococcus); painful; onset 2nd-3rd decade; worsens in summer; blistering resolves over weeks → leaves hyper/hypopigmentation. Ix: skin biopsy (acantholysis in all epidermal layers - 'dilapidated brick wall'; no DIF [direct immunofluorescence] deposition - differentiates from pemphigus); ATP2C1 sequencing. Mx: avoid triggers (friction, heat, moisture control); antibacterial/antifungal cover (Staph/Candida); topical tacrolimus (non-steroidal maintenance); botulinum toxin (axillary - reduces sweating - effective); topical/oral antibiotics; laser ablation (CO2 laser); surgical dermabrasion (recalcitrant); retinoids. Note: confused with pemphigus vulgaris (DIF negative, acantholysis ALL layers, familial - ATP2C1); botulinum toxin for axillary disease - reduces sweating, reduces flares."},
    {"name": "Pityriasis rubra pilaris", "aliases": ["PRP", "pityriasis pilaris"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Pityriasis rubra pilaris"), ("Mx", "treatment of Pityriasis rubra pilaris"), ("Staging", "staging of Pityriasis rubra pilaris"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Pityriasis rubra pilaris")], "summary": "Papulosquamous disorder characterised by salmon-orange erythroderma, follicular keratosis, and palmoplantar keratoderma. Classification (Griffiths): Type I (adult classical - 55%; cephalocaudal spread, islands of sparing, palm/sole orange hyperkeratosis; good prognosis - resolves 3 yr); Type III (juvenile classical - similar to Type I in children); Type II (adult atypical - chronic, ichthyosiform, alopecia); Type V (atypical juvenile - familial, CARD14 mutation - chronic; associated with CARD14-related papulosquamous eruption). Pathophysiology: idiopathic in most; CARD14 mutations (familial, Type V); association with HIV, internal malignancy (paraneoplastic PRP). Sx: follicular keratotic papules coalescing → orange-red scaly plaques with islands of normal skin (pathognomonic in Type I); palmoplantar orangey hyperkeratosis (PPK); cephalocaudal progression → erythroderma. Ix: clinical + biopsy (follicular plugging, alternating orthokeratosis/parakeratosis - 'chessboard pattern' on pathology). Mx: retinoids (acitretin - systemic - mainstay); methotrexate; cyclosporin; biologics (ustekinumab, TNF inhibitors - for refractory); PUVA. Note: 'islands of sparing' = pathognomonic (areas of normal skin within erythroderma); distinguish from psoriasis (islands of sparing, orange colour, follicular papules); Type I spontaneously remits; CARD14 mutation in familial."},
    {"name": "Pityriasis lichenoides chronica", "aliases": ["PLC", "pityriasis lichenoides", "PLEVA", "pityriasis lichenoides et varioliformis acuta"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Pityriasis lichenoides chronica"), ("Mx", "treatment of Pityriasis lichenoides chronica"), ("Staging", "staging of Pityriasis lichenoides chronica"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Pityriasis lichenoides chronica")], "summary": "Spectrum of T-cell-mediated papulosquamous disorders from acute ulceronecrotic (PLEVA) to chronic (PLC) forms. Pathophysiology: clonal CD8+ T-cell reaction (atypical T-cells in skin); some consider spectrum between inflammatory dermatosis and lymphoma (rare progression to lymphoma - MF/LyP); association with infections (parvovirus B19, EBV, HIV, Toxoplasma). PLC: chronic, scaling papules and plaques (months-years); trunk, proximal limbs; hyperpigmented/hypopigmented macules post-resolution; minimal symptoms; waxes and wanes. PLEVA (acute): abrupt onset; erythematous papulovesicles → haemorrhagic crusting → necrotic punched-out ulcers; systemic symptoms (fever - Mucha-Habermann disease - severe variant with fever, ulcers). Ix: biopsy (wedge-shaped T-cell infiltrate, epidermal spongiosis, lymphocyte exocytosis - CD8+ predominant; lichenoid pattern). Mx: tetracyclines (doxycycline - first-line - anti-inflammatory); NB-UVB phototherapy; methotrexate (PLEVA/severe PLC); topical steroids; observation (PLC often self-limiting). Note: risk of lymphoma transformation low but real (monitor for persistent clonal disease); distinguish from LyP (lymphomatoid papulosis - recurring, self-healing papules - CD30+; higher lymphoma risk)."},
    {"name": "Intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy", "aliases": ["obstetric cholestasis", "cholestasis of pregnancy"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy"), ("Mx", "treatment of Intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy"), ("Staging", "staging of Intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Intrahepatic cholestasis of pregnancy")], "summary": "Cholestatic liver disorder unique to pregnancy; associated with adverse perinatal outcomes. Pathophysiology: genetic predisposition (ABCB4, ABCB11, ATP8B1 - bile salt transporter mutations) + oestrogen/progesterone triggers → impaired bile acid transport → bile acid accumulation in maternal serum; bile acids cross placenta → fetal cardiac arrhythmia + placental dysfunction. Sx: pruritus (intense, characteristic - palms/soles, worse at night, no primary skin lesion - excoriation marks only), onset 2nd-3rd trimester; resolves within 2-4 wk postpartum; jaundice in <10%; dark urine, pale stools (cholestatic). Complications: stillbirth (association - risk increases with bile acids >40 μmol/L; sudden fetal death - mechanism unclear - cardiac arrhythmia likely), preterm birth (often iatrogenic), meconium-stained liquor, fetal distress, neonatal RDS. Ix: serum bile acids (>10 μmol/L - diagnostic; >40 μmol/L = high risk; measure fasting); ↑ALT/AST (mild-moderate); ↑bilirubin (variable); ↑GGT; exclude other causes (hepatitis, biliary obstruction, AFLP - acute fatty liver of pregnancy). Mx: ursodeoxycholic acid (UDCA - mainstay; reduces bile acids, pruritus, improves LFTs; benefit on fetal outcomes debated - PITCH trial no mortality benefit but improves pruritus); early delivery (36-37 wk if bile acids >40 μmol/L; 38-39 wk if milder; individualised); fetal monitoring (CTG - though limitations for predicting sudden death). Note: recurs in future pregnancies (~60-70%); avoid OCP/progesterone-only pill in history of ICP; notify patient re: family members (inherited); bile acids >40 μmol/L = high-risk threshold for active delivery planning."},
    {"name": "Vulvodynia", "aliases": ["vulvar vestibulitis", "vestibulodynia", "localised provoked vestibulodynia", "LPV", "chronic vulvar pain"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Vulvodynia"), ("Mx", "treatment of Vulvodynia"), ("Staging", "staging of Vulvodynia"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Vulvodynia")], "summary": "Chronic vulvar pain without identifiable cause; multifactorial aetiology. Types: localised (vestibulodynia - most common - pain at vulvar vestibule, provoked by touch/penetration - dyspareunia, tampon insertion pain); generalised (unprovoked - constant aching/burning). Pathophysiology: peripheral sensitisation (increased vulvar nerve density - C-fibres); central sensitisation; pelvic floor hypertonicity; psychosocial factors (anxiety, depression, sexual dysfunction, relationship distress); prior genital trauma/surgery; hormonal changes (low oestrogen - atrophic changes). Diagnosis of exclusion: exclude infection (candida, herpes, STIs), dermatoses (lichen sclerosus, LP - biopsy if uncertain), neurological cause. Ix: cotton-swab test (Q-tip test - map pain on vestibule - allodynia); vulvoscopy; biopsy (only if lesion present - rule out dermatosis). Mx: multidisciplinary (pelvic floor physiotherapy - first-line; psychological/psychosexual therapy; topical lignocaine/lidocaine; low-dose TCAs [amitriptyline]/SNRIs [duloxetine]; gabapentin; vestibulectomy [surgical - for localised refractory vestibulodynia - 80% success]; hormonal: local oestrogen/testosterone cream). Note: frequently misdiagnosed as recurrent candidiasis or dismissed; pelvic floor physiotherapy essential component; vestibulectomy reserved for refractory localised vestibulodynia with demonstrated allodynia on Q-tip test."},
    {"name": "Lichen sclerosus", "aliases": ["lichen sclerosus et atrophicus", "vulvar lichen sclerosus", "penile lichen sclerosus", "balanitis xerotica obliterans", "BXO"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Lichen sclerosus"), ("Mx", "treatment of Lichen sclerosus"), ("Staging", "staging of Lichen sclerosus"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Lichen sclerosus")], "summary": "Chronic inflammatory skin disease causing atrophy, sclerosis, and architectural distortion; predominantly anogenital. Pathophysiology: autoimmune (Th1-mediated); HLA association; associated with other autoimmune disease (thyroid disease, vitiligo, RA - 20%); dysregulated autoantibodies to ECM-1 and BP180. Sites: vulva (most common in females - ~90% anogenital), glans penis/prepuce (balanitis xerotica obliterans - BXO, in males), anal, extragenital (wrists, upper back, neck - less common). Sx: females - intense pruritus (vulvar), pale white atrophic plaques ('white crinkled cigarette paper' appearance), figure-of-8 distribution (vulva + perianal), loss of labia minora architecture (resorption), clitoral hood fusion/phimosis; dyspareunia, dysuria, fissuring; males - BXO - white plaques glans/prepuce → phimosis → urinary obstruction. Complications: vulvar squamous cell carcinoma (SCC - 2-5% lifetime risk; closely linked to differentiated vulvar intraepithelial neoplasia [dVIN]); urinary/sexual dysfunction. Ix: clinical + biopsy (basal layer vacuolation, sclerosis - homogenised collagen, lichenoid infiltrate). Mx: ultra-potent topical corticosteroid (clobetasol propionate 0.05% - first-line; reduces symptoms + risks of SCC if used consistently; lifelong maintenance likely needed); tacrolimus (alternative steroid-sparing); regular surveillance (vulvoscopy annually - for VIN/SCC). Note: lifelong treatment required; annual surveillance essential (SCC risk); male BXO → circumcision + meatal dilatation if urinary obstruction; LS ≠ lichen planus (LS: pale, atrophic, figure-8; LP: violaceous, Wickham striae, erosive)."},
    {"name": "Lichen simplex chronicus", "aliases": ["LSC", "neurodermatitis", "circumscribed neurodermatitis", "lichen simplex"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Lichen simplex chronicus"), ("Mx", "treatment of Lichen simplex chronicus"), ("Staging", "staging of Lichen simplex chronicus"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Lichen simplex chronicus")], "summary": "Thickened lichenified skin from chronic scratching/rubbing cycle. Pathophysiology: itch-scratch cycle → epidermal hyperplasia (acanthosis, hypergranulosis) + lichenification (skin thickening with accentuated skin markings); may be primary (idiopathic itch) or secondary (superimposed on atopic eczema, contact dermatitis, psoriasis, lichen sclerosus). Sites: easily accessible areas - nape of neck (posterior), lower leg (shin), anogenital (vulva, scrotum - see vulvodynia overlap), ankle, forearm, scalp. Sx: intensely pruritic, well-demarcated, thickened, hyperpigmented plaques; exaggerated skin markings (lichenification); scratch marks/excoriations; psychological stress often exacerbating. Ix: clinical; biopsy if uncertain (psoriasiform hyperplasia, hypergranulosis, fibrosis - no diagnostic features). Mx: break the itch-scratch cycle - potent topical corticosteroids (occlusion enhances penetration); tacrolimus/pimecrolimus; sedating antihistamines (chlorphenamine - reduce nocturnal scratching); doxepin; psychotherapy (habit reversal, CBT); intralesional triamcinolone (refractory); address underlying skin condition. Note: often associated with anxiety/OCD spectrum; address psychological triggers; distinguish from psoriasis (silvery scale, Koebner, extensor distribution), plaque eczema (atopy history, family history)."},
    {"name": "Genitourinary syndrome of menopause", "aliases": ["GSM", "atrophic vaginitis", "vaginal atrophy", "vulvovaginal atrophy", "VVA", "urogenital atrophy", "atrophic vaginosis"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Genitourinary syndrome of menopause"), ("Mx", "treatment of Genitourinary syndrome of menopause"), ("Staging", "staging of Genitourinary syndrome of menopause"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Genitourinary syndrome of menopause")], "summary": "Chronic, progressive hypoestrogenic changes affecting genitourinary tissues; replaced term 'atrophic vaginitis'. Pathophysiology: declining oestrogen (menopause, lactation, GNRH analogues, aromatase inhibitors, anti-oestrogens) → vaginal/vulvar epithelial atrophy + loss of glycogen → alkaline pH → dysbiosis (loss of lactobacilli) → symptoms; affects vulva, vagina, urethra, bladder. Sx: vaginal dryness, dyspareunia (superficial - most bothersome), vaginal discharge (watery/yellow), post-coital bleeding, vulvar pruritus/burning; urinary: frequency, urgency, recurrent UTIs, dysuria, urge incontinence; NOT associated with hot flushes (unlike vasomotor sx). Ix: clinical; pH >5 (vaginal pH >5 = atrophic); maturation index (VM - preponderance of parabasal cells); speculum (pale, smooth - loss of rugae, petechiae, friability). Mx: first-line - local/topical oestrogen (vaginal oestrogen - cream [Ovestin/Premarin], pessary, ring - highly effective, minimal systemic absorption - safe in most women including breast cancer survivors with caution); lubricants/moisturisers (non-hormonal - water-based lubricants for dyspareunia; hyaluronic acid moisturisers); systemic HRT (if systemic vasomotor sx also present); ospemifene (oral SERM - alternative if topical not tolerated); prasterone (vaginal DHEA). Note: GSM ≠ menopausal hot flushes (different mechanism - doesn't improve without treatment; hot flushes may resolve spontaneously); unlike vasomotor symptoms, GSM doesn't improve spontaneously - worsens without treatment; local oestrogen very safe - does not significantly raise serum oestrogen."},
    {"name": "Cervical ectropion", "aliases": ["cervical erosion", "cervical ectopy", "columnar ectopy"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Cervical ectropion"), ("Mx", "treatment of Cervical ectropion"), ("Staging", "staging of Cervical ectropion"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Cervical ectropion")], "summary": "Eversion of columnar endocervical epithelium onto ectocervix (squamocolumnar junction visible on ectocervix); normal anatomical variant in many women. Pathophysiology: oestrogen-dependent - columnar epithelium 'rolls out'; physiological in: adolescents, pregnancy (most extensive), OCP users; regression after menopause (columnar epithelium recedes into endocervical canal). Sx: asymptomatic (most common - incidental finding on speculum exam); symptoms: post-coital bleeding (contact bleeding - common presenting complaint), excess vaginal discharge (cervical mucus from columnar cells); dyspareunia (less common); NO pain typically. Ix: speculum examination (salmon-pink/reddish area around os - granular/velvety - normal columnar mucosa); colposcopy (if atypical - acetic acid: no acetowhitening in ectropion; rule out CIN/cervical cancer); Pap smear/HPV test (routine cervical screening - not diagnostic for ectropion). Mx: most asymptomatic - reassurance (physiological); symptomatic post-coital bleeding - ablation (cryotherapy, cold coagulation - destroys columnar epithelium → squamous metaplasia); treat concurrent cervicitis (STI screen if discharge - gonorrhoea, chlamydia). Note: reassure patient - not cancer, not an 'erosion' (avoid term); post-coital bleeding always requires cervical smear + colposcopy to exclude CIN/cervical cancer before attributing to ectropion."},
    {"name": "Uterine polyp", "aliases": ["endometrial polyp", "intrauterine polyp", "uterine endometrial polyp"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Uterine polyp"), ("Mx", "treatment of Uterine polyp"), ("Staging", "staging of Uterine polyp"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Uterine polyp")], "summary": "Localised overgrowth of endometrial glands and stroma projecting into uterine cavity. Epidemiology: common (25% of women with abnormal uterine bleeding); perimenopausal women most affected; incidence increases with age; obesity, tamoxifen use, unopposed oestrogen are risk factors. Sx: abnormal uterine bleeding (AUB) - intermenstrual bleeding most common (post-coital bleeding, heavy periods, postmenopausal bleeding - all warrant investigation); may be asymptomatic (incidental on USS). Complications: rarely malignant (~1-2% - endometrial carcinoma arising in polyp; higher with: postmenopausal bleeding, size >1.5 cm, obesity, tamoxifen use, diabetes). Ix: transvaginal ultrasound (TVUS - hyperechoic endometrial lesion ± colour Doppler single feeding vessel - 'pedicle artery sign'); saline infusion sonohysterography (SIS - best non-invasive); hysteroscopy (gold standard - direct visualisation + directed biopsy). Mx: hysteroscopic polypectomy (gold standard - resection + histology mandatory to exclude malignancy); watchful waiting (asymptomatic, small, premenopausal - may spontaneously regress); levonorgestrel IUD (reduces recurrence in premenopausal). Note: tamoxifen (breast cancer adjuvant) → uterine polyps + endometrial hyperplasia/cancer (stimulates endometrial oestrogen receptors); any postmenopausal bleeding → refer for investigation; hysteroscopic removal + histology required in all symptomatic."},
    {"name": "Parametritis", "aliases": ["pelvic cellulitis", "parametrial cellulitis", "broad ligament cellulitis", "puerperal parametritis"], "utd": [("Dx", "diagnosis of Parametritis"), ("Mx", "treatment of Parametritis"), ("Staging", "staging of Parametritis"), ("Adjuvant Rx", "adjuvant therapy Parametritis")], "summary": "Infection/inflammation of parametrium (pelvic connective tissue lateral to uterus). Pathophysiology: spread from endometrium (endometritis) → parametrial connective tissue (broad ligament, cardinal ligaments) → cellulitis → abscess (if untreated). Causes: puerperal infection (post-partum/post-caesarean - most common context), post-abortion infection (post-procedural), PID extension (ascending genital tract infection). Organisms: polymicrobial (Group A Streptococcus, E. coli, Bacteroides - anaerobes, Group B Strep). Sx: fever (often high - 39-40°C), lower abdominal/pelvic pain, uterine tenderness (boggy), parametrial tenderness (on vaginal examination - 'board-like' parametrium laterally), tachycardia; risk of extension → pelvic/broad ligament abscess → sepsis, ileus. Ix: clinical + investigations (FBC - leucocytosis; CRP elevated; blood cultures; endocervical/high vaginal swab; USS pelvis - rule out abscess, though CT/MRI more sensitive for parametrial extension). Mx: IV antibiotics (broad-spectrum - IV ampicillin-sulbactam; or IV clindamycin + gentamicin - covers anaerobes + gram-negatives; continue IV until afebrile 24-48 h → oral step-down); drainage if abscess; surgical drainage if refractory. Note: distinguish from simple endometritis (uterine tenderness only - earlier stage - antibiotics resolve) vs parametritis (lateral extension - more serious - risk of abscess); postpartum fever + lateral parametrial tenderness = parametritis until proven otherwise."},

